{"id":"1304.4822","submitter":"Stefano Sanvito","authors":"Aaron Hurley, Nadjib Baadji and Stefano Sanvito","title":"Detection of the electrostatic spin crossover effect in magnetic\n  molecules","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.88.054409","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Scanning tunneling microscopy (STM) can be used to detect inelastic spin\ntransitions in magnetic nano-structures comprising only a handful of atoms.\nHere we demonstrate that STM can uniquely identify the electrostatic spin\ncrossover effect, whereby the exchange interaction between two magnetic centers\nin a magnetic molecule changes sign as a function of an external electric\nfield. The fingerprint of such effect is a large drop in the differential\nconductance as the bias increases. Crucially in the case of a magnetic dimer\nthe spin crossover transition inverts the order between the ground state and\nthe first excited state, but does not change their symmetry. This means that at\nboth sides of the conductance drop associated to the spin crossover transition\nthere are two inelastic transition between the same states. The corresponding\nconductance steps split identically in a magnetic field and provide a unique\nway to identify the electrostatic spin crossover.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Apr 2013 13:36:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-15"}
